<li id="cite_note-26"><b><a href="#cite_ref-26" title="">^</a></b> For an extravagant and hypnotic cinematic employment of this technique, recontructing the ancient psychological context of storytelling and oral transmission, watch Wojciech Jerzy Has's unusual and influential 1965 Polish film <i>The Saragossa Manuscript</i>, restored and released in video in 2000 by Martin Scorsese and Francis Ford Coppola in dedication to Jerry Garcia. <a href="http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/27/saragossa.html" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.brightlightsfilm.com/27/saragossa.html" rel="nofollow">[5]</a><a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005Y6YR" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005Y6YR" rel="nofollow">[6]</a> Also, in a more directly middle eastern vein, try the video or DVD of <a href="/wiki/Pier_Paolo_Pasolini" title="Pier Paolo Pasolini">Pier Paolo Pasolini</a>'s luxuriant <i>Arabian Nights</i><a href="http://www.moviemartyr.com/1974/arabiannights.htm" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.moviemartyr.com/1974/arabiannights.htm" rel="nofollow">[7]</a> which the Arab scholar Robert Irwin [see note 25 below] praised as ". . .wonderful. . .the only version made for adults."</li>
